Llan Ffestiniog, Merioneth, Wales}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid6242166\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid6242166 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Could you give your name and address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Well - do you want my proper name? Frank Evans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Where do you live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Bryn Olew, Ffestiniog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Are you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 When did you marry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 It was during the war. 1916. December 1916. I was in the Army then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Where were you born, and when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 I was born in Ffestiniog. In - 1890 - oh, something - 18 - well anyway I'm 80 next birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 How many years did you lived in the house in which you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Well roughly about eight or nine years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Where did you go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Oh to - Pengwern Villa. And then after that here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 You then moved up here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, well you see my father built these two houses together, Bryn Olew, and then you see my brother lived in one and I lived in the other.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 And you've lived here ever since?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
Now wait a minute, after I married I went to live in Bodwyn in Station Road, Ffestiniog, where my mother-in-law lived. And then you see on my father's death the house came to me, this house. So of course I came to live here then, with my mothe
r. And then of course after she died then it was me and the wife. I've got a good story now. Shall I tell it in English or Welsh? I remember watching my father writing his will, and he used to keep the will up on top of the cupboard. And I remember one da
y
 I went and had a look at it. And I remember chatting with a father about what he was going to put in his will and he said, you know, well, I'm going to leave this house to you after I die, and you're to come and live with your mother. Well, I said, you k
n
ow, I might be married by then and the wife probably won't want to live with my mother. Oh yes, he said, I didn't think of that. And I said, you know, look at the moment I'm - paying rent to my mother-in-law, and my father - thought about it and realized 
h
e'd made a mistake because - my brother was already getting the next door house on his death. And he realized, you know, that I'd be paying rent, at - you know, to my mother-in-law. So what he did was get tenant for us. This was, you know, to prevent me h
a
ving - to pay rent and - because I didn't get possession of our house straight away. And then of course I left - rented Tinant to John, you know, he's still there. I sold it to him in fact. Which was probably a mistake really. I mean I wouldn't have got T
inant at all if it hadn't been for the fact that I'd seen the will and told my father that - you know I was being - done down.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Do you remember why your family moved from one house to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, yes, I do. Which year was it, I came back from
 the Army in 1919. I went to Egypt for about three years you see and - I came back and lived with mother-in-law, I remember that very well. And I remember going into this shop. And I used to buy - always buy things from Jones - from Manod. And I mean she 
bought there so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 obviously}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
 I bought goods and things there. And I went there one day to get some goods and the goods came to a pound and a ha'penny and I didn't have the ha'penny. So the old bitch changed a whole pound to just get that ha'penny. I told my mo
ther-in-law, I won't go there again. She changed a pound just to get a ha'penny you know. I told my mother-}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 in-law}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
 that, I wouldn't go there ever again, and I didn't either. And I'd just come out of the Army too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
Well I have two brothers and one sister, they're all dead now though. My sister was buried - what - about two months ago and she was ninety.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 They were all older than you were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, yes, I was the youngest. And I was the first to 
marry, no I wasn't, my step-sister was first. She - she got married before I did. And - and I was the first of the boys to marry. The other two married afterwards. That was while I was in the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 How many years were there between the children and what order did they come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
Well there were about two years between - my brother - well he was a step-brother too you know. In fact they both were. 'Cos you see, my father married three times, and you see he had a son and a daughter from the first mar
riage and one son from the second and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 only}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264  me with the third.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 A boy was the eldest, it was boy, girl and then two boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, that's right. Yes, but - that's right, it went, son, daughter, another boy and then me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Do you remember how many years there were between you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
Well there were two years between my younger brother and me, and then there were about six or seven years between the eldest and me. And then, I'd say there were about - well ten years between my sister and me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 You mean your sister was the oldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Do you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 No I don't, that's a pretty difficult sum to do. My father died when he was about sixty-five or sixty-six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Could you tell me when your father died, what year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
I can't remember you know. I used to have some records. It's on the gravestone. You could go down to the graveyard and look at it. See my father died about sixty - sixty-nine. He died pretty young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 You don't know what year it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 No, I couldn't tell you. Not offhand you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Where did your father come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Well - you see, my father's story is recorded in the National Library of Wales. There's a book about my father's history and it's been on
 television and so on, my father used to work in the quarry. He was ten when he first went. He was born in Penial Terrace, and he'd get up at six o'clock in the morning and he'd walk to the quarry in Balaenau to be there by seven o'clock. They had to walk
 
in those days. And then he went on strike in the quarry. And - I - was talking to Evan Hughes about his father, you know, Maolod's grandfather. You see, he was the ringleader. Him and Ellis Hughes, from Cymerau, a farm on the outskirts of Ffestiniog. And 
t
hey came out on strike because they were fighting for - you know, for - for rights, for the right for workers to have more wages, and you see because they'd come out they didn't get their jobs back. And you see there wasn't enough guts in the - in the qua
r
rymen to stay out until the ringleaders were reinstated. Because there wasn't such a thing as a union in those days. And so there wasn't any work for these people. And you see what happened was that - Malod's father - grandfather - opened - a butchers sho
p
 in Penial Terrace, and - Ellis Hughes from Cymerau opened a coal business. And at the same time my father left the quarry and - opened a grocers business, at Liverpool house. And then afterwards he had a shop in Trawsrynydd. He had two shops in those day
s. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 
And I remember him saying many time that he used to get up at four o'clock in the morning and set off with a horse and cart down to Port Madoc to fetch coal, to fetch flour, and he had to leave at four o'clock in the morning for the reason that they had 
to be back across the cob, which is the Estuary, near Port Madoc, because - there's been a big sea wall built there now - but then the sea wall didn't exist, so they had to cross the cob before the tide came in. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 And then you see, if they - if they failed t
o do that well the - the road through Llanfrothen wasn't built then, so they had to stay in Port Madoc so that's why they had to start off at four o'clock in the morning, in order to go and get the coal and the flour off the boats which came in to Port Ma
doc harbour and I remember him saying that many times.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Do you remember when the quarry strike was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 I'm not sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 But was your father a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, he was. He was pretty young in those days. All the dates you know are in this book 
- that's been printed about my father's history. And then there's one pamphlet published by the War Office, a Naval Review, and that's got his picture in and everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 What did he do after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Well you see, the thing was, after the grocers s
hop, well you see he'd always wanted to be a vet or a doctor, one or the other, it didn't matter, and so he used to spend all his money on books. Books about being a vet or a doctor, and his mother and father, there would be about five or six of them, did
n
't have the money to make him - to send him to be a doctor or a farrier, so they - so he had to spend all his money on books and he studied to be a vet on his own, and then he started studying experiments in oil, how to make oil mixtures and that and he u
s
ed to buy old horses and treat them and cure them. I mean I remember those. I remember him buying one horse for about two pounds and he'd been kicked and he had an enormous great lump on his leg, and I went there with a paintbrush and painted on this oil 
and - in order to make the swelling go down, and of course the horse got well again. And then - one time - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 Lord}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264  John }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 Sanger's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
 Circus came to Blaenau, this is in about 1902, and he had a lot of horses in those days and this story is at home, at my home. And 
my father went there to - you know to - to introduce the oil to him and John Sander said, you don't think we'd come to a place like this to get cures for our - our horses and medicines for our horses. Well, my father said, I haven't come here to sell you 
anything. I've just come to introduce it. May I have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4857542\charrsid11011264 look}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
 at some of your horses, he said. And there were about a hundred and fifty horses there. 'Cos the - no one had heard of motor cars. And my father pointed to one horse and said, that one's not it goo
d condition. And my father went up and touched him, touched his back like this, and he found something straight away. And he painted a certain point on his back. He found out what was wrong with the horse, and he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4857542\charrsid11011264  said to th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 e man, I can cure this horse with
in a week. And, he said, look if you can cure that horse within a week or fortnight I'll be very pleased to see you again. And he - my father said, you know, would you mind if I gave him a dose now? No, no at all, he said. Providing I can get one of the c
h
aps to - one or two of the chaps to help you. Why? my father said. Oh, you can't give him a dose without having one or two people there to hold him. To twist his nose. You know what that is don't you? I'll manage it, my father said. No you won't, said the
 
man. He - it's dangerous, he'll kick. No, you leave it to me, my father said. My father went up and patted the horse on its back and got hold of it like this and he put his hand in his mouth and - with a bottle in his hand started playing around with his 
tongue. Good God, said Lord John }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 Sanger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
, I've been with horses all my life and I've never seen that done. You see, the horse was drinking it as my father was playing with his tongue. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 Sanger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid854880\charrsid11011264  said, well I've never seen that - anything like that in all my 
life. And my father said to him, well you tell one of your horsemen to do exactly as I've done every day - because I mean it's unnatural to make a horse lift its head up to dose it, and a horse naturally drinks with its head down. And when you lift his he
ad up and twist his nose well he's choking. And John }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 Sanger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
 realized what he was saying and said, you know, that point had never dawned on him. And - of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4857542\charrsid11011264 course}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
 the horse did get better, and they were customers of ours all their lives. No matter where they were with the circus they used to send for the oil. And I remember that, you know, from 1902 at least.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Is that what your father did all his life after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Yes, that's right, once the business was built up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Did he ever do any other jobs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 No, he gave up the grocers shop. Once the - oil business started up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6242166 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 Do you ever remember young father being out of work?
