\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12287980 FE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
Yes, that's right. No, no, wait a minute, you - you're wrong. There's a house there now, where this old chapel used to be. You know, Medwin lives there. On the right hand side as you go up that little road. Penfrith y
ou know. And you see there was a chapel there before, and you know it was called Hen }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16650296\charrsid11011264 Capel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid854880\charrsid11011264 
. If you looked up the deeds you'd probably find it. And was a story of this - of this relative of mine preaching there. And I've got the books at home about it. And 
here's a story for you. While we're on this. When I got the details from Somerset House, now - this man - William Evans, well his mother and father were - Evan Roberts and that was what his mother and father were called. And you see, his father, Evan Robe
r
ts, was - hung for stealing sheep. And you see, his son went into the Ministry, but because his father had been hung for stealing sheep he changed his name to William Evans. And that's how I get the William in my name you see, my real name is Francis Will
i
am Evans. That's my real name. And the William bit come in after William Evans. And if you look into the family tree you find very sort of prominent people. Vets and - preachers and - you know. And as I've communicated with some of the family, found them 
and things - it's a very long story, and it was one of them that invented the siren, he was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And then he came over to Admiralty House, his sister told me this. And he was the one that invented the siren in the time of the war. He came over to Admiralty house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Very interesting story of - of - you know - of William Evans and his immediate relatives. Yes, and I've got all the history. And I - you see, I got this dresser after the old boy - you see, after my uncle died I got this - this dres
ser. He - it was very old you know, it was at least a hundred years old. And you see what I did in fact was to - to exchange it with something that Robert - Manod's house had because I wanted something more modern. It was very silly really because obvious
ly the old one was worth much more than what I got. In fact it was three hundred years old. And it was supposed to be in the family. But I mean I didn't really know anything about the history of it then, but of course it's gone now.
