and the painter's ordered all the paper and everything. In fact he's painting part of the contract. But then my uncle went bad you see, and naturally they stopped and didn't finish the other room. Oh everything's got to stop, the preacher said. No by God,
 
I said. He said, you see this cupboard here, I want that. And I said, you're not having it. Because it's a fixture, I said. Oh we want it, he said. And I said to him, well look, who's going to repair the damage if you drag that cupboard off - off the wall
?
 There was no screws in there, they were nails you know, who's going to pay for the damage? Oh, he said, you can easily find paper to match this room. And I said to him, what the hell do you think I am, a bloody fool? He told me to go and see the solicito
r
, and if I've done any injustice you can go and see him. And I told the solicitor you know that the Masefields refused to let the old couple have the sewing machine, which was only two pounds, in lieu of my board and lodgings. So I said to the solicitor t
o
 - to make out a bill - to - ask the old couple to make out a bill as if I'd been living in a hotel, which would - the solicitor informed me would be about seven or eight pound, and throw that at the preacher and his wife. So the solicitor did, and told t
h
em that it was their own bloody fault. 'Cos these people were very kind and all they wanted was that little machine and you said you wouldn't give it to them, you wouldn't pay for the paper either. And I think Frank Evans told you to go to hell, and I thi
